TY  - JOUR
T1  - Sex as a Discriminating Variable in Organizational Reward Decisions
AU  - Reif, William E.
AU  - Newstrom, John W.
AU  - St. Louis, Robert D.
Y1  - 1976/09/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255612
DO  - 10.5465/255612
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 469
EP  - 476
VL  - 19
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents a study which examined whether gender is a predictor of reward preferences in an organization. An organizational rewards is anything that employees perceive as need satisfying. Rewards can range from traditional economic rewards, such as salary and fringe benefits, and psychosocial rewards, such as praise from a supervisor and having a respected place in the informal work group. In the study, thirty three reward items were chosen to depict the organizational rewards system. Findings suggest that both men and women at the same organizational level respond differently to rewards. It proves that sex is a discriminating variable in terms of reward preferences.
AB  - The article presents a study which examined whether gender is a predictor of reward preferences in an organization. An organizational rewards is anything that employees perceive as need satisfying. Rewards can range from traditional economic rewards, such as salary and fringe benefits, and psychosocial rewards, such as praise from a supervisor and having a respected place in the informal work group. In the study, thirty three reward items were chosen to depict the organizational rewards system. Findings suggest that both men and women at the same organizational level respond differently to rewards. It proves that sex is a discriminating variable in terms of reward preferences.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255612
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255612
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

