TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effects of Reward Contingency and Participative Decision Making on Intrinsically and Extrinsically Motivating Tasks
AU  - Turnage, Janet J.
AU  - Muchinsky, Paul M.
Y1  - 1976/09/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255614
DO  - 10.5465/255614
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 482
EP  - 489
VL  - 19
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article focuses on a study which examined the effects of reward contingency and participative decision making on intrinsically and extrinsically motivating tasks. E. L. Deci has examined changes in intrinsic motivation as a consequence of external reinforcement. He distinguished two classes of motivation, namely, intrinsic motivation and extrinsic motivation. He suggests that differential increases or decreases in intrinsic motivation occur as a function of the type of reward given for an activity. He concluded that the effects of both intrinsic and extrinsic motivation are not additive. An analysis of variance showed differences between tasks in terms of performance time, intrinsic motivation and interest and difficulty ratings. The study also revealed that the effects of external rewards and participation on performance and intrinsic motivation are different for different jobs.
AB  - The article focuses on a study which examined the effects of reward contingency and participative decision making on intrinsically and extrinsically motivating tasks. E. L. Deci has examined changes in intrinsic motivation as a consequence of external reinforcement. He distinguished two classes of motivation, namely, intrinsic motivation and extrinsic motivation. He suggests that differential increases or decreases in intrinsic motivation occur as a function of the type of reward given for an activity. He concluded that the effects of both intrinsic and extrinsic motivation are not additive. An analysis of variance showed differences between tasks in terms of performance time, intrinsic motivation and interest and difficulty ratings. The study also revealed that the effects of external rewards and participation on performance and intrinsic motivation are different for different jobs.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255614
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255614
Y2  - 2026/04/24
